              Notation

              • x : state, x∈S=S+∪{0},

                • x0 or x(0) : initial state for discrete / continuous situation

                • there are Nx​ distinct states for each time step

                • x~ tend to represent extend states like x~k=[xk,yk]⊤

              • w(t) : disturbance

              • u(t) : control input , u∈U, there are Nu distinct control inputs for each time step

              • μ(t,x) : admissible control law (policy), u(t)∼μ(t,x)

                • π : policy, π∗ optimal policy

              • f(x,u) : system evolution

                • for continuous system: x˙(τ)=f(x(τ),u(τ))

                • for discrete system : xk+1=fk(xk,uk,wk)

              • gk(x,u) : cost for each step ,

                • gN(x) is the cost for discrete terminal state

                • h(x) is the cost for continuous terminal state

              • J(t,x) : cost function, J∗ optimal policy

              • N : time horizon

              • Pij : probability of transition from state i to state j, Pr(xk+1=j|xk=i,uk=μ(i))=Pij(μ(i))

              • q(i,u) : expectation of cost q(i,u)=Ew|x=i,u=u[g(x,u,w)]

              • p(t)​ : trajectory

              Probability

              • x∼N(μ,σ2) then x2∼N(μ2+σ2,2σ4+4μ2σ2)​

              • x∼N(μ,σ2) then Cx∼N(Cμ,C2σ2)

              Quadratic

              f(x)=ax2+bx+c

              • f′(x)=0→x=−b2a​​

              • f(x)|f′(x)=0=−b24a+c

              Problem Statement

              Dynamics

              xk+1=fk(xk,uk,wk)x˙=f(x,u,w)

              Cost

              Jπ=E[gN+∑k=0N−1gk(xk,uk,wk)]

              • Jπ∗ : optimal cost Jπ∗=max Jπ

              Open Loop : control inputs are determined at beginning

              • expected cost

              J(x)=E(X1,W0|x0=x)[gN(xN)+∑k=0N−1gk(xk,u¯k,wk)]

              • Number of Open Loop Strategies : NuN​ all the possible path from start to end

                 

              Closed Loop : u(t)→μ(t,x) control inputs depend on the measured state

              • expected cost

              Jπ(x)=E(X1,W0|x0=x)[gN(xN)+∑k=0N−1gk(xk,μk(xk),wk)]

              • Number of Close Loop Strategies : Nu(NuNx)N−1 (number of state stay constant) or Nu∑kNxk all possible path for unique set of all reachable states ∑kNxk​

                 

              Open Loop vs Closed Loop

              • open loop is special case of closed loop

              • open never performs better than closed loop

              • for deterministic problem , closed loop is not efficient as open loop

               

              [DPA]Dynamic Programming Algorithm

              Jk(x)=minu∈U(x)E(wk|xk=x,uk=u)[gk(xk,uk,wk)+Jk+1(f(xk,uk,wk))]JN(x)=gN(x)

              • Number of Minimizations : number of reachable states ∑kNxk

              • when there is no disturbance wk​, it can be solved by forward DPA

              general state :

              Example : xk+1=fk(xk,xk−1,uk,uk−1,wk), x~k+1=(xk+1yk+1sk+1)=(fk(xk,yk,uk,sk,wk)ykuk) where yk=xk−1, sk=uk−1

              Infinite Horizon Problems : N→∞ and time invariant cost gk→g

              • Recursion

                Jk(x)=minu∈U(x)E(w|x=x,u=u)[g(x,u,w)+Jk+1(f(x,u,w))]JN(x)=gN(x)

              • N→∞ it becomes BE, if JN converge, then J(x)=J∗(x)

               

              [BE]Bellman Equation

              J∗(x)=minu∈U(x)E(w|x=x,u=u)[g(x,u,w)+J∗(f(x,u,w))]
              V∗(x)=min/maxu∈U[r(x,u)+α∑x′Px,x′(u)V∗(x′)]

              • convergence of IHP

              [SSP]Stochastic Shortest Path : the transition from state i to state j is governed by Pr(wk+1=j|xk=i,uk=u)=Pij

              Jk(i)=minu∈U(i)(q(i,u)+∑j=0nPij(u)Jk+1(j))

              • Pij is time-invariant, Pij≥0

              • cost-free terminal state P00(u)=1 and g(0,u,0)=0 ∀u∈U(0)​

              • In the terminal state, any admissible control action is optimal

              [VI] Value Iteration

              Vl+1(i)=minu∈U(i)(q(i,u)+α∑j=1nPij(u)Vl(j))

              • infinite number of iteration to converge to optimum J∗, when to stop : threshold for ‖Vl+1(i)−Vl(i)‖

              • complexity : O(n2p), n is the number of states, p is the possible control inputs

              • synchronous update

                Vl+1(i)=minu∈U(i)(q(i,u)+α∑j=1nPij(u)Vl(j))

                V[:] = V_

              [PI] Policy Iteration

              • Value Update:

                Vl+1(i)=q(i,u)+α∑j=1nPij(u)Vl(j)

                • complexity : O(n3), n is the number of states, solve linear system

              • Policy Improvement:

                μl+1(i)=argminu∈U(i)(q(i,u)+α∑j=1nPij(u)Vl+1(j))

                • complexity : O(n2p), n is the number of states, p is the possible control inputs

              • cost-free terminal state and proper policy (Jπ(i)≠∞, every state could reach 0), PI converges to optimum after a finite number of steps

              • Asynchronous PI

                • any number of value updates in between policy updates

                • any number of states updated at each value update

                • any number of states updated at each policy update

              • converge to the same optimal cost as VI if the solution is unique

              • has unique solution ⇔ I−P invertible ⇔ remove terminal state 0 S→S+​

              • discounted problem can arbitrary initialized

              • discounted problem I−αP always invertible

              • values of each state at each iteration should decrease of remain the same.

              [LP]Linear Programming : used to solve the BE and yields optimal cost J∗ for SSP

              maxV∑i∈S+V(i)subject to V(i)≤(q(i,u)+α∑j=1nPij(u)V(j)) ∀u∈U(i),∀i∈S+

              • to transform to form min f⊤xsub Ax≤b

                • A=−[I−αPu1⋮I−αPuNu] where Pui=[P11(ui)⋯P1Nx(ui)⋮⋱⋮PNx1(ui)⋯PNxNx(ui)]

                • b=−[bu1⋮buNu] where buNi=[r(1,ui)⋮r(Nx,ui)]​

                • minimize problem f=−1, maximize problem f=1

              Discounted Problem : decay exponentially

              J~π~(i)=E(X~1,W~0|x~0=i)[∑k=0N−1αkg~(x~k,u~k,w~k)]

              • finite steps

              • arbitrary initial

              Auxiliary Stochastic Shortest Path : equivalent Discounted Problem

              Dynamics :

              pw|x,u(j|i,u)=αP~ij(u)pw|x,u(0|i,u)=1−αpw|x,u(j|0,u)=1pw|x,u(0|0,u)=1

              Cost :

              g(xk,uk,wk)=α−1g~(xk,uk,wk)

              • one to one mapping to discounted problem

              • Example : given discount factor α=0.4

               

              [SP]Shortest Path Problem

              [DFS] Deterministic Finite State Problem :

              xk+1=fk(xk,uk)J=gN(xN)+∑k=0N−1gk(xk,uk)

              [SP] Shortest Path : in a graph, find a path from node s∈V to t∈V that has a smallest length

              Q∗=argminQ∈Qs,t=argminQ∈Qs,t∑h=1q−1cih,ih+1

              • symmetric : forward DPA and backward DPA are the same for this problem

              • no negative cycles : ∀i∈V,Q∈Qi,i,JQ≥0 , if negative, there will exist infinite loop​

              • N≤|V|−1

              • DFS to SP

                 

              • why it can be solved by forward DPA (Jk←Jk+1)? it's deterministic

              • why it can be solved by backward DPA (Jk←Jk−1)? it can be converted to a deterministic DP problem.

              [HMM]Hidden Markov Model :

              • measurement model : z is measure in transition from i to j

              Mij(z)=pz|x,w(z|i,j)

               

              Viterbi Algorithm : Given measured sequence Z1=(z1,⋯,zN), we want to find the most likely state trajectory X0=(x0,⋯,xN)

              maxX0 p(X0,Z1)=p(x0)∏k=1NPxk−1xkMxk−1xk(zk)⇔minX0(cs,(0,x0)+∑k=1Nc(k−1,xk−1),(k,xk))

              where

              cs,(0,x0)={−ln(p(x0))p(x0)>0∞p(x0)=0c(k−1,xk−1),(k,xk)={−ln(Pxk−1xkMxk−1xk(zk))Pxk−1xkMxk−1xk(zk)>0∞Pxk−1xkMxk−1xk(zk)=0c(N−1,xN−1)=0

              • DPA can be applied to already solve for the most likely state trajectory up until now.

              • Future measurements can change the most likely trajectory for pasttime steps

              [LCA]Label Correcting Algorithm

              1. s→OPEN, set ds=0,dj=∞ ∀j∈V/{s}

              2. OPEN→{i}∪OPEN

              3. ∀j∈Ni if (di+cij)<dj and (di+cij)<dt, dj←di+ci,j, j.parent←i; if j≠t , OPEN←OPEN∪{j}

              4. |OPEN|>0 goto 2

              [HJB]Hamilton-Jacobian-Bellman Equation

              0=minu∈U(g(x,u)+∂J∗(t,x)∂t+∂J∗(t,x)∂xf(x,u))

              where J∗(T,x)=h(x)

              Pontryagin's Minimum Principle :

              H(x,u,p)=g(x,u)+p⊤f(x,u)p˙(t)=−∂H(x,u,p)∂x|x(t)u(t)p(t)⊤p(T)=∂h(x)∂x|x(T)⊤u(t)=argminu∈UH(x(t),u,p(t))x˙(t)=f(x(t),u(t))

              • necessary condition for optimal cost

              • Bang-Bang Control : u∈{a,b}​

                • Example : x¨=u,a<0<b , normally u={bt∈[0,t]at∈[t,T]

              • minimize total time T: g(x,u)=1, since T=∫0T1dτ

              optimal trajectory

              H(x(t),u(t),p(t))=−∂J(t,x)∂t|x(t)=constant
